This article is a Presidential Proclamation issued by President Barack Obama on December 4, 2009, declaring December 7th as National Pearl Harbor Remembrance Day. The proclamation pays tribute to the brave men and women who sacrificed their lives during the surprise attack on Pearl Harbor by the Imperial Japanese in 1941. It highlights the resilience and courage displayed by American service members who defended their positions and cared for the wounded during the attack. The proclamation also emphasizes the unity and resolve shown by Americans across the country in response to Pearl Harbor, with many joining the Armed Forces to defend the nation. The Congress has designated December 7th as National Pearl Harbor Remembrance Day, and President Obama encourages all Americans to observe this day with appropriate ceremonies and activities. He also urges federal agencies and interested organizations to fly the flag at half-staff in honor of those who died at Pearl Harbor.